05721nam a22008295i 9781501754616DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017546167 a10.1515/97815017546162doi  a(DE-B1597)566280  a(OCoLC)1248758878  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDD231.L8bL59 2021 7aHIS0270902bisacsh04a355.0092aB223  aNP 4617qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/127856:1 aLockenour, Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDragonslayer :bThe Legend of Erich Ludendorff in the Weimar Republic and Third Reich /cJay Lockenour. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b22 b&w halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBattlegrounds: Cornell Studies in Military History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Mythic Life -- t2. Victor of Liège and Tannenberg -- t3. The Feldherr -- t4. Putschist -- t5. Prophet: Tannenberg League and Deutsche Gotterkenntnis -- t6. Duelist: Ludendorff, Hindenburg, Hitler -- t7. Ludendorff in the Third Reich -- t8. Siegfried’s Death -- tEpilogue: Kriemhild’s Revenge -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this fascinating biography of the infamous ideologue Erich Ludendorff, Jay Lockenour complicates the classic depiction of this German World War I hero. Erich Ludendorff created for himself a persona that secured his place as one of the most prominent (and despicable) Germans of the twentieth century. With boundless energy and an obsession with detail, Ludendorff ascended to power and solidified a stable, public position among Germany's most influential. Between 1914 and his death in 1937, he was a war hero, a dictator, a right-wing activist, a failed putschist, a presidential candidate, a publisher, and a would-be prophet. He guided Germany's effort in the Great War between 1916 and 1918 and, importantly, set the tone for a politics of victimhood and revenge in the post-war era. Dragonslayer explores Ludendorff's life after 1918, arguing that the strange or unhinged personal traits most historians attribute to mental collapse were, in fact, integral to Ludendorff's political strategy. Lockenour asserts that Ludendorff patterned himself, sometimes consciously and sometimes unconsciously, on the dragon-slaying hero of Germanic mythology, Siegfried, hero of epic poem, the Niebelungenlied, and much admired by German nationalists. The symbolic power of this myth allowed Ludendorff to embody many Germans' fantasies of revenge after defeat in 1918, keeping him relevant to political discourse despite his failure to hold high office or cultivate a mass following post-World War I.Lockenour reveals the influence that Ludendorff's postwar career had on Germany's political culture and radical right during this tumultuous era. It is a tale as fabulist as fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGeneralszGermanyvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 70(DE-588)4065109-50(DE-627)10612059X0(DE-576)209156864aWeimarer Republik2gnd 70(DE-588)4132742-10(DE-627)1056853720(DE-576)209638133aGeneral2gnd 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh  aOperation Michael, unrestricted submarine warfare, german radical right, collapse of the weimar republic, Knight og the long knnives, great war.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK P